</caption>
<paragraph blockId="27.[178,1085,1148,1257]" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[295,373,1148,1170]" captionStart="Figs 36-43" captionStartId="26.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[186,1078,212,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-65@26.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figs 36-43: Micrillus distortus nov.sp.: (36) habitus; (37) forebody; (38) male sternite VII; (39) male sternite VIII; (40-41) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (42) ventral process of aedeagus in ventral view; (43) internal structure of aedeagus in dorsal view. Scale bars: 36-37: 1.0 mm; 38- 43: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301303/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.1 times as long as broad and almost as broad as head, noticeably tapering posteriad; surface glossy and with extremely fine, barely noticeable micropunctation; on either side of midline with series of few (4-5) larger punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[178,1086,1273,1354]" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[255,330,1273,1295]" captionStart="Figs 36-43" captionStartId="26.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[186,1078,212,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-65@26.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figs 36-43: Micrillus distortus nov.sp.: (36) habitus; (37) forebody; (38) male sternite VII; (39) male sternite VIII; (40-41) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (42) ventral process of aedeagus in ventral view; (43) internal structure of aedeagus in dorsal view. Scale bars: 36-37: 1.0 mm; 38- 43: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301303/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as pronotum; punctation dense and distinct. Hind wing fully developed. Metatarsomere I approximately as long as the combined length of II and III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[178,1085,1369,1449]" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506">Abdomen slightly narrower than elytra; punctation rather dense, fine, but distinct; interstices with very shallow microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe; posterior margin of tergite VIII strongly convex.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[178,1085,1465,1574]" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506">
: sternite VII (
<figureCitation box="[346,421,1465,1487]" captionStart="Figs 36-43" captionStartId="26.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[186,1078,212,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-65@26.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figs 36-43: Micrillus distortus nov.sp.: (36) habitus; (37) forebody; (38) male sternite VII; (39) male sternite VIII; (40-41) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (42) ventral process of aedeagus in ventral view; (43) internal structure of aedeagus in dorsal view. Scale bars: 36-37: 1.0 mm; 38- 43: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301303/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
) moderately transverse, posterior margin concave in the middle, pubescence unmodified; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[571,645,1494,1516]" captionStart="Figs 36-43" captionStartId="26.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[186,1078,212,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-65@26.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figs 36-43: Micrillus distortus nov.sp.: (36) habitus; (37) forebody; (38) male sternite VII; (39) male sternite VIII; (40-41) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (42) ventral process of aedeagus in ventral view; (43) internal structure of aedeagus in dorsal view. Scale bars: 36-37: 1.0 mm; 38- 43: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301303/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
) oblong, with deep and very narrow posterior excision; aedeagus 
<quantity box="[438,587,1523,1545]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="1506" unit="mm" value="0.425" valueMax="0.45" valueMin="0.4">0.40-0.45 mm</quantity>
long, strongly asymmetric, and of distinctive shape; internal sac with long and asymmetric sclerotized structure.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="1507" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[178,1086,218,445]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">
Comparative notes: This species is characterized by the distinctive morphology of the aedeagus and additionally distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Eppelsheim" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[822,932,248,270]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[822,932,248,270]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">M. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1931" box="[948,1078,249,270]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scymbalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis box="[948,1078,249,270]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">M. nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1858" box="[224,366,277,299]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lithocharis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavescens">
<emphasis box="[224,366,277,299]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">M. flavescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by different head shape (flattened, posteriorly not tapering, not oblong) and the almost obsolete microsculpture of the head, from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Eppelsheim" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[882,996,306,328]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[882,996,306,328]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">M. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scymbalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">M. nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also by shorter antennae with less oblong preapical antennomeres, and from 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">M. asperiventris</emphasis>
by the less convex, posteriorly distinctly tapering pronotum with much sparser and finer punctation, the longer and more slender antennae (preapical antennomeres not distinctly transverse), and the denser punctation of the abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="1507" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="28.[178,1086,461,570]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">
Distribution and natural history: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[793,985,461,483]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distortus">
<emphasis box="[793,985,461,483]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">Micrillus distortus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was discovered in two localities in 
<collectingRegion box="[464,701,490,512]" country="Laos" name="Khammouan" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">Khammouane province</collectingRegion>
in central 
<collectingCountry box="[813,865,491,512]" name="Laos" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">Laos</collectingCountry>
, one in 
<collectingCountry box="[948,1037,490,512]" name="Vietnam" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, and one in northern 
<collectingCountry box="[345,435,519,541]" name="Thailand" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[450,521,519,541]" captionStart="Map 4" captionStartId="27.[178,223,1091,1111]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1066]" captionTargetId="figure-174@27.[178,1085,212,1066]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="Map 4: Distributions of Micrillus distortus nov.sp. (triangles) and M. suturalis (CAMERON) (circles) in the Oriental region, based on examined records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301305" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301305/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">Map 4</figureCitation>
). The specimens from the 
<typeStatus box="[800,844,520,541]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1507">type</typeStatus>
locality were collected in a degraded primary forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
